  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a real issue that can undermine the performance of individuals from underrepresented groups. As a fitness trainer who’s been working with people of all backgrounds, I’ve seen how anxiety about being judged can affect anyone—whether it’s in a gym or a classroom. For instance, when I’ve worked with students who’ve been told they’re not 'good at math,' even if they’re capable, their confidence drops. This is similar to stereotype threat: the fear that one’s group is stereotyped can trigger stress that hinders performance. I think we absolutely should address it, but not with big, sweeping policies that might not fit everyone’s lives. In my community here in Washington DC, where I volunteer with local schools, I’ve noticed that simple, practical steps work best. For example, creating a safe space where students feel heard and valued—like having open discussions about challenges without judgment—can make a huge difference. I also believe in modeling positive behavior: showing up as someone who’s willing to learn and make mistakes helps kids see that it’s okay to struggle. Since I’m a fitness trainer, I know that building confidence through small, consistent efforts is key. So, instead of focusing on one-size-fits-all solutions, we should tailor approaches to the individual. This isn’t just about fixing the problem—it’s about fostering an environment where everyone feels they belong. After all, when people feel safe, they can thrive.",
